    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-22T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="1038"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1038">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 (China) American Radio Service/70:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fletcher</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-22T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 22, 1940—1 [<hi rend="italic">6</hi>] p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 23—4 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s 159, October 2, 6 p.m. American Radio Service. I have today received
                    a reply from my Japanese colleague to protest lodged in accordance with the
                    instruction contained in the telegram under reference. The reply states that
                    since the equipment was received from the French authorities he was forced to
                    consider my protest as having been “misdirected”.</p>
                <p>In view of the evasive nature of the above reply and of the unsatisfactory reply
                    from the French Consul to my protest to him (as reported in my despatch number
                    1211, October 15, 1940 to the <pb facs="0935" n="927" xml:id="pg_927"/>
                        Embassy<note n="86" xml:id="d1038fn86">Not printed.</note>), it is suggested
                    that the Embassy make appropriate representations on the matter to the French
                    and Japanese authorities at Peiping. I consider that further action here would
                    only delay settlement of the question and would serve no useful purpose.</p>
                <p>Sent to Peiping. Repeated to the Department, Chungking, and land wire to
                    Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Fletcher</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
